values:
Monday

Went to debating society in the evening.  The motion was "The House Believes that Islam is Given a Bad Press".  I wasn't a particularly good debate.  The proposition were a little unsure of their argument I think.  John spent almost 3 minutes of his time talking about his model, which was basically the put on more public service broadcasts on islam.  This is far enough, but he kind of skirted around the issue of whether or not islam was given a bad press, which was of course what the debate ought to have been about.  Becauses of props argument, the opp were a little constrained as to their arguments.  Personally I would have attacked John on his lack of definition of the term islam - whether he meant religion, culture or both.  I would also have attacked his lack of argument in terms of whether it is given a bad press or not.  Opp didn't do this though and the debate ended up more of a discussion of the truthfulness of the press which is kinda related, but I wouldn't have made it the ONLY issue.
The next speaker from the Prop was new.  He didn't speak English too well and he didn't really understand what he was doing.  He gave us a bit of a lecture on how Islam isn't really violent, in fact the Bible is much more violent word for word.  This would have been ok, had he made it clear that it was the presses fault that we didn't know this, but this didn't happen.  He upset the chair man (who is v religious) by attacking Christianity as a violent religion.
This left John in a difficult position when he came to do his speech.  He made an ok job out of it, but it was still a pretty rubbish debate all in all.  For that reason, most people voted to abstain.
The really drama happened outside of the actual debate.  Ryan and Nick weren't talking over a joke of Ryan's that wasn't that funny.  John was very unimpressed and told Ryan so, which lead to another, fairly loud argument on the way home.


Tuesday

Finally absolutely finished my Politics essay, it just needs printing and handing in.  Yay!  I'm fairly happy with it.  I'm hoping for a good 2.1 for it.  In other work news, I went to my last proper History seminar.  From next week onwards we are planning and then doing our assessed presentations, and then starting work on our essays.  There is no exam for this part of the course, so that is a massive relief.
In the evening I went out with the debating society on a "bar crawl".  I put that in speech marks because it wasn't so much a crawl as a sit and drink in Bowland bar before moving on to Furness bar.  It was good fun though.  We decided not to talk shop (although there was some discussion of the recent IV's, but this is classed as social) and talked about more normal stuff instead.  I got back at about 12.  Made something to eat and then watched some dvds for a while.  I feel asleep by about 2, but was woken up by Dan at about 3.  He was banging on the doors and shouting "I hate this flat" - what a wanker!

Wednesday

Having a bad house mates day.  Am already feeling a bit grumpy from last night.  I had forgiven him, we are students after all, but then this morning I found a note tacked to the fridge.  Kelly wants us all to have one self in the fridge and freezer each.  This is fair enough (though a bit of an pain),but it's the fact that she and Dan wrote out a note instead of actually talking to people about it!  I mean we live together, yet me and Lucy are made to feel like social outcasts just because we have friends outside of the flat.
I hate to be so bitchy, but I have to get this off my chest.  From day one Kelly has made Lucy and I feel as though we aren't worth speaking too.  I don't expect to be best of friends with her.  Afterall, we don't have much in common.  However, I expect some acknowledgement that I exist and am not some kind of second class person.  Both Lucy and I have tried very hard to be nice to her.  I used to talk to her every time she and I were in the kitchen, even though all I got was one word answers.  I tried she did not.  I used to think it was because she was shy or insecure or something.  I still think this is the case, but I have lost all sympathy for her due to her actions and her total disregard for me and Lucy.

I was up at 10.30 this morning dispite not getting to sleep until very late last night.  I was very pleased with myself; it's very rare i'm up before 11.00 on Saturday mornings.  Furthermore, I was busy all day.

I started off the day by doing my laundry - fun fun fun.  While I was waiting I worked on my politics essay.  I had lunch and continued with my essay only stopping for a break when Adam rang at 2pm.  By 3pm I had pretty much finished by esssay (appart from having to get a reference for one item, I need to go to the library for that) and decided to head to the gym.  I returned at about 4.30, sorted out all my papers and sort of tided my room.  All I need to do now is put away my clean clothes and change the bed (but I think i'll do that tomorrow.  I'm going out tonight and won't appreciate it as much as I will on Sunday night).

So all in all I am very pleased with myself.  Not bad for a Saturday at all.  Now I need to jump into the shower.  Saturday night is Sugar House night, and I want to look my best!

I didn't get to bed until 3.30 this morning.  I stayed up drinking beer and later tea with Frankie.  It was fun because we have so much in common.  Felt a little guilty though as it was very flirty and there seems to be some kind of attration between the two of us.  

I woke up at 9am the next morning, but as I had a bad sore throat and headache, I made a cup of tea and went back to bed.  Stephen was already up, apparently his girlfriend is visiting today so I think he wanted to tidy his room and get ready for her.  I woke up again at around 11am, but didn't finally get up until mid-day.  I ate breakfast in the flat with Doughy before going to the swimming pool for a swim.  It turned out to be a really good little pool.  It even had two lap lanes!  I didn't stay to long, as I still felt a little unwell.

Back at the flat I messed around on the computer a little, read the newspaper with my flat mates and rang Adam.  We had a deep conversation about our relationship which ended with us taking the opposing sides to the ones which we took in a previous argument before we went away.  I ended the conversation feeling a little happier about our relationship than I had done in previous days.  I suppose it was silly of me to think that our relationship would be the same as ever.  I'm just going to have to adapt to this new situation.  I need to think carefully about the future however, afterall university is all about opening one's mind to new possibilites.

I made sweet and sour chicken for tea, which was very nice, although I cooked far to much rice and had to bin at least a portion and a half.  Tonight I am going to quiz night.  I promise myself here and now that I will not stay out until 3am again.  I have a History lecture at 11am, although as they have not given us a reading list, or even a list of the titles of lectures I can do no prior reading.  Hopefully they will suggest to us which books we should buy tomorrow.  I also have a Philosopy and Politics lecture, as well as my first meeting of the Debating Society at 7pm.  I think I will try and do some of my reading between lectures.  It is going to be a very busy day.  Hopefully abstaining from alcohol tonight will help my Freshers' 'Flu.

I didn't get up today until 12.10pm because I had stayed up until 2.30am watching Peter Kay videos with my flat mates.  I ate brunch with Steven and discussed our plans for the day.  Shortly afterwards Lucy arrived and we set off out of the flat and on to Lancaster.  It took about 15 minutes to get into the city centre.  It isn't that far away, but there were loads of stops on campus and loads of people were gettting on and off.  

In Lancaster we had a look around a few grocers before deciding that we would buy all our food from Sainsbury's.  I didn't have any meat back at the flat, so I took the oppertunity of buying packs to chicken breasts, mincemeat etc.  The bags were very heavy and we were very glad that the bus station was so close to the store.  It wasn't much food carting 5 large bags of shopping up two flights of stairs.  We put it all away and I started chopping up all the vegetables that I had bought to make a stew.  I sat with Lucy talking and reading the paper while it cooked.

Everybody seems to be doing their own thing just now.  Lucy has gone to the flat next door to talk to Zoe.  She doesn't actually like her much and finds her hard to talk to, but feels deeply sorry for her as she is so quiet and none of her own flat mates talk to her.  I'm going to get ready for tonight very soon.  The theme is "Aliens and Out of Space".  I wont be going in costume - I haven't even got a clue for a costume!  I expect I will hang around with flat 8 people as they are going, but I don't think my own flat mates are.  I feel a little strange around them now.  I didn't behave too well on Wednesday night... but that's a whole different story.

Saturday

Had a fairly mundane day at work.  Nothing of note really happened.  When I arrived home I found Adam's key on my bedside table and wondered whether he would have been able to get into his house when he returned home from mine this morning.  I rang him to find out and also whether we were going to The Hightown as per usual for a quiet Saturday night.  He told me that as he had forgotten his key he had been unable to return home and had gone to his mum's friend's house instead before starting work at 2.  Luckily his mum had now returned home and would definitely be there on Sunday morning, meaning he could come over and stay with me.

We drank two drinks each at the pub.  Adam decided that he was going to try some Whiskey as apparently he had spent all day on Booze at work and it had been "calling him".  He tried to convince me that he like it, however I could tell by the look on his face that really he would have preferred a beer as per usual.

Sunday

It was very quiet at work today.  I was told this was because there was a Man U vs Liverpool match on at 12 so people had decided to stay at home and watch that as opposed to coming shopping.  I was very efficient in cooking and did not run out of food at all, which I was very pleased about.  

After work I attempted going to the gym, but couldn't set my mind to it and ended up coming home after a 15 minute jog.  I was a bit upset because I had a bit of an incident in the car:  I was at the Tesco lights.  They were on green, but about to change, so I went straight on without stopping, however the cars turning right had already started to turn, and we almost crossed paths.  I kept wondering whether it was my fault and I went to late.  I keep worrying about it, as I don't really trust my driving skill.  Nothing happened though, so I guess everything but my confidence is fine.

Spent the rest of Sunday afternoon with my lovely family reading the paper and reading my book.  After tea I went up to my room and spent 4 hours reading "Middlemarch" - still haven't finished the bloody thing!  I came downstairs at 10pm to watch "Monsters' Ball".  I really enjoyed it, although it was really very graphic both sexually and in terms of violence.  The execution scene, I found was particularly distressing.  I enjoyed the ending though, as it was very different from the one which I was expecting, and in my opinion more optimistic.

Monday

Had a very bad day.  I had recurring panic attacks and felt very depressed indeed, although I couldn't work out why I felt so sad.  From time to time I do feel very depressed; it upsets me even more that I know, logically I have almost everything I could possibly want and have had a very fortunate life up to this point.  Felt so bad that at about 12.30 I rang Adam and begged him to come around right away.  He came within the hour and after receiving a nice long hug of him, I began to feel much better about myself.  


Tuesday

Feeling much better today.  I should have really of gone to the gym, but didn't really feel like it.  I went for a wander around Southport instead.  I bought a lovely sparkly belt from Topshop which I really should not have got, but bought anyway.  I met up with Adam in cafe Nero and showed him my purchase.  He didn't seem very impressed, but I'm sure he'll like it better once it's one.  He is like any man really in that he just can't see how an outfit goes together.  We both felt very cuddly and affectionate today and this was commented on by the Nero staff who asked us to "get a room".  Personally I think that was really quite rude, as we were only holding hands, and I would have got into lots of trouble if I had made similar comments at my place of work.

My life has been rated:
See what your rating is!
Created by bart666

Went to bed rather later than I intended as I met Adam after work and when to the pub. Somehow we managed to make one pint and a bottle of Bud last 2 full hours. We didn't return home until after 11.30 and went straight to bed. I woke up at 7.30 the next morning feeling a bit sick. I think I may be coming down with something. Sophie has already acquired a cold after only two days back at High School. I think I may be in the same situation, as yesterday after running on the treadmill I started to cough. My mum drove me to work today, as she had to drive my father to the station. He had wanted her to drive him to Manchester Airport as he was leaving for a four day conference in Italy, but my mother had refused, sighting that she needed to go into Southport instead and would not have the time to take him. Nothing of real note happened today in work. I gave up my usual cooking job to Natalie. I had heard from Carol that she had really wanted to cook in the cafe and once I left, she was going to cook every week. I told Natalie that if she would have asked to swap, I would have been more than happy, as I get very bored doing the same job each week. Instead of cooking I was on dishwasher duties and spent the whole day washing a continuous stream of other peoples dirty dishes. It was quiet therapeutic in a way as it gave me time to think and daydream. In addition, one can work at ones on pace as opposed to taking shouted orders from other members of the team. After work I had very little planned for the afternoon and spent most of my time reading in my bedroom. Still haven't finished Middlemarch, although I am enjoying it very much. I always feel very sleepy in the afternoons, particularly after work and often end up taking a nap when I intend to read my book. Later on in the afternoon my mum cooked a wonderful Sunday Lunch of roast chicken. Adam came around shortly after and most of the evening was spent with him doing his maths problems and I watching Casualty on the television. It was a quite interesting story for a change: a group of asylum seekers where trapped in building that had fallen in on them due to the councils neglect. It made me think of the real life asylum seekers in Liverpool, housed by the council in condemned council blocks, which no white scouser would ever dream of inhabiting. It made me think of the stupidity of the anti-asylum arguments that go round, such as "they take our homes, they take our jobs" etc. To be honest, I don't so much blame the government or even local councils for housing asylum seekers in such dreadful housing - their hands are pretty much tied by their electorate who would be up in arms against any additional money spent on those poor people. What angers me the most is the general attitude that is propagated by the right-wing press and that colours peoples attitude and makes any sensible argument put forward by the government seem ridiculous. For example, one of my very good friends told me that she was very against immigration of any sort - that people should basically stay in their own countries - after all, she wouldn't dream of moving out of England, so why should they. I tried to tell her that there was a whole world out there; why limit yourself to just one country, particularly if yours is ravaged by war or famine or both? She wouldn't listen to my argument, and she is the product of a middleclass lifestyle and decent education. In short she is one of the people who should be the freest from prejudice and manipulation by the press. I really wish I knew a way to remedy this situation, even on a local level, but at times it seems impossible. While I was writing this post Adam started to criticise my style. I feel this is very unjust and while I recognise that I write very differently for any other Live Journal user I have ever read, I believe this to be no bad thing. He finds my writing to formal and others may criticise me for this also. In justification, I try to be as well read as I can be and am particularly fond of the classics. In addition I have read other diarists such as Alan Cark and Vera Brittain to name just two and feel that these books have made an impression on the way I feel I should write, and the type of journal I wish to create. Indeed I am very proud of my journal despite the fact it contradicts some of the so-called Live Journal rules that everyone else seems to follow. On a lighter subject Max was very cute today while we were sat in the living room watching television. He fell asleep on the remote control! I wasn't very successful at taking pictures at him however. He doesn't like the flash and he watched me wearily as I attempted to take another one of him in a more relaxed position.

I woke up later than I anticipated this morning and ate a late breakfast at around 10am.  As it was raining I asked my mum to let me have the car to drive to the gym instead of taking public transport (and getting very wet).  She agreed and I drove her to work at around 11am before heading to the gym.  Despite not training as hard in the last few weeks I was surprised by my performance.  I ran for about 15mins at 10.0 (approx 8.5min mile); did 10mins on the cross trainer; used the step machine for 10mins; cycled for 15mins and finished my cardio with a 10 minute session on the rowing machine.  Afterwards I did some tummy crunching and reverse curls on my stomach.

Feeling happy with myself I ate lunch in the gym cafe while I read Glamour magazine before heading home.  I scared myself on the way home.  I took one of the corners on the road up to Hightown a little to fast (approx 35 miles per hour) and felt the wheels skid a bit on the wet road.  It shows that pride really does come before a fall as I had been bragging to my mother that it had been a whole year now since I passed my driving test and as yet I had had no accidents.  Situations like this are useful however as I believe I was starting to be over confident in the car and situations like this remind me just how dangerous the road can be and that it needs my full respect and attention.

Had a less interesting time at home.  I continued my reading of Middlemarch and had a short nap before coming on the computer to update live journal and talk to a few friends who are on msn.  Tonight I am going out with the girls (and guys) from work.  I shall take my camera and this time remember to use the flash!  It good they have decided to go out again as this will probably be my last social with them until Christmas.  It's less fortunate however that I am in work tomorrow at 6am so I won't be partaking in Shorrocks, which is ultimately where Jenny and at least Laura will be.  I'm also conscious that I should be saving my money and so really don't want another blow out night like Wednesday - particularly as I have just been payed and there is way to much temptation when my bank balance seems more healthy.

A minor disappointment came today.  Adam has heard from Eurocamp, I have not.  Perhaps it is just the post in Hightown, but I'm starting to worry that I won't get an interview at all.  It would be a sad irony if Adam spent all summer off in France and I stacking shelves!

Spent most of the day in bed through illness.  I finished off "An Anatomy of Terror" and started "Middlemarch" later in the afternoon.  Found the relaxation of a day mostly spent in bed fairly enjoyable as by mid-morning I was feeling better, although still a little under the weather with a slight temperature.  Sent mum to Chemist to buy some over the counter medicine, however she returned saying that the chemist had instead made an appointment for me to see the doctor.  Was not happy at all:  firstly I was feeling better and only wanted some medication in case I became worse in the night; secondly I know very well from past experience that the doctor will just hand out antibiotics and that will be all.  Unless I am in any real pain, or suffering for extended periods I will not take antibiotics.  One can become resistant to them and then they will be useless when I really needed them and besides it will stop my my pill working as it should.  I phoned up to cancel the appointment - I just hope I don't get sick over night again.

My illness is an obvious sign of my not taking the care that I need to of my body.  Although I'm not prone to colds etc I do find that in some ways my body is more delicate than most of my peer group.  For example I'm pretty sure todays bout of illness was due to too many late night and too much alcohol.  My raised blood pressure also co-in sided with my drinking more alcohol than usual (last day of college etc).  It seems unfair that I seem to suffer like this:  I take more exercise than most of my friends put together; I do not drink as much as most of my peer group; I don't smoke and my diet is generally good with very little salt/fast food etc.  It looks very much at the moment that I will always have to be very careful about my lifestyle in order to maintain the good health I have now.  It seems a little unfair when I see the excess of others, but I suppose it is better to know now of the weaknesses of my body than not know and create ill health later in life.

Health aside, I also sorted out a few university bits and pieces including all the stuff about the student support services.  I really need to sort out about finding my dyslexia report to send of to Lancaster.  Apparently most departments give dyslexic students stickers for their work to tell lecturers to take in to account our conditions.  I think this is a fairly good idea, although I think I will struggle less as most of my work will be produced on PC with all essays needed to be written, drafted and re-written as a matter of course.

Hopefully tomorrow will be a better day for me.  I definitely hope so!  I've got work on Friday which I would rather not be ill for as I really need the money to top up my uni fund.  Hopefully I will see Adam tomorrow.  I think he was in work today and I have had no contact with him as yet.

Monday

Absolutely terrible day in work.  It had been too busy on Sunday night for Carol to get any shopping done so I spent the 1 hour prep time rushing round like a headless chicken trying to get the cafe ready for opening at 9.  Looked on the rota and discovered that it would be just me and Jen until 10am; prayed that we wouldn't be too busy until that point.  I think most people in Formby did not think that Tesco would be open until 10 so we had a relatively quiet hour - much better than I had expected.  Unfortunately by 10.30 it had picked up and became one of the busiest days ever.  We rang for help but were ignored (checkouts were in the shit too - you can tell when they keep asking for "all till trained staff to checkouts" over and over again.)  Finally I cornered Jane (Personnel Manager) while on my way up for a break.  When I came back down, she was busy clearing tables, obviously she had been unable to find anyone to help out and had resorted to doing it herself.  Jenny came in at about 1pm when we were at our busiest.  She said I looked extremely stressed and definitely needed to go the pub with her that night.  

At 3pm my shift ended and I finally got out of the cafe.  Felt a little guilty leaving my work colleagues there - but Tescos only pays authorised overtime so I would not have received any recognition or pay if I had continued to work.  Carol often works more than she is paid for.  For example on Friday she worked a 9 hour shift with only a 30min break (illegal).  Jen worked out Tesco owes her 4 hours pay just for this week.  She'll never see it though - she won't even recieve a shitty "Value Award".  I refuse to go above the hours I am paid for- if they think you can manage on less people they will reduce the number of hours on a department, thus work becomes consistently harder for all on the department.  Its shit - we work harder for less benefits, in a less enjoyable environment while Alistair (Store Manager) gets an even bigger bonus.  It's a silly strategy for Tesco to take, just look at Marks & Spencer's (co-incidentally where Alistair used to work) who cut costs, and service and ended up in the shit.  Thank god I will be out of there soon.  Anyway, Tesco rant over.  

The rest of the afternoon was spent in my bedroom.  Read a little more of the Alan Clark diaries, listened to my new Athlete CD and had a short nap.  Felt totally relaxed and rested.  I arranged to meet Jen at the Railway at 8.30.  As it turned out she did not arrive until 8.50 but I have come to expect her to be always tardy.  I got a seat outside under the heaters (it was lucky I arrived on time, as outside was quickly filling up).  Jenny arrived very tired even though she had done very little all day.  She has been partying and drinking a little too hard recently - as I suppose I have to.  She ordered a lime and soda, I was naughty and had a Carling and blackcurrant, promising it would be my last one for a while and I would go back on my diet which I have practically forget since the exam results.  We spent much of the next hour bashing our customers and making fun of their stupidity, until Adam arrived at about 10.  We continued talking until about 11pm when we decided we would go home - everyone felt very tired.

Tuesday

Had a very lazy morning.  Work up about 9.30ish and got up to make breakfast in bed for Adam.  Lay in until about 11 when Adam had decided he had wasted enough of the day.  I needed to go into Formby to visit my bank to set up my student account; I also had some books out that needed renewing or returning.  While in the village, I met up with Carol, Gemma and then a little later Rene from the coffee shop.  It's always funny seeing people from work in the real world.  I think it's because in work virtually everyone looks a state - I NEVER wear makeup and rarely wear my contacts; there doesn't seem a point when I always return home covered in baked beans and smelling of bacon fat.  I think whenever we see each other outside work we are always surprised at just home attractive we all are!

Spent the afternoon reading through the literature sent by the bank about my new account.  I also took a look at Lancaster's web page.  I've printed out the list of lectures for Politics; I found a very useful guide to philosophy which details week by week what I will be studying (if I chose that course) and the types of assessments that are set.  I had a look at the history department too, but their information is less detailed.  I think I am fairly sure that I will study History and Philosophy now as my sub sids.  They are the courses that Lancaster suggests that a politics student should take anyway.  Adam thinks I should study Economics - I think this is unnecessary as I will do a unit on political economy which will be good enough for me (I don't fancy doing much maths at uni) and anyway the economics units are in short supply and Management students are first in the queue to sit these classes.

After tea I went to Studio strength.  It was really hot in the aerobics studio and it was much harder work than usual.  Mrs Grimes (now known as Susan, which still feels strange) congratulated me on my results which was nice.  I hate the fact that the aerobics studio is covered in mirrors.  I had to go at the front of the class so I could not avoid scrutinising my figure.  Felt that I definetly looked as though I had been over indulging in the last few days (eating biscuits, cake, not going to the gym for 4 WHOLE DAYS! etc) and that I must return to my regime immediately.  No more crappy food, alcohol etc until 7th September (The Last Supper) when I will allow myself the day off as I will be eating out and then going to Shorrocks (for which one must ALWAYS be hideously drunk!)

Tomorrow I think I will go to the gym in Southport, maybe even have a swim.

Monday I returned home from the hair dressers at about 3pm. My hair looked absolutely fantastic. I had been a little worried that it would not be worth the money but I definitly felt it was worth it. I spent most of the rest of the afternoon watching tv (I did not want to partake in any activity that may damage my hair in anyway. Anyway here are some pictures of me and adam before the prom.
Everyone looked absolutely amazing at the prom. There were some lovely outfits. Its a shame about the music. The college decided to hire DJ Sticks (because he was cheap) so we had to endure joke after joke about his disability in between listen to music dating from about 5 years ago. The room picked up at about 11.30 pm when he started playing the classics (9 to 5; Bon Jo-vi etc) but had tapered out by about 1am when Adam and I decided to leave. I had work in the morning and felt like I had drank a little too much wine. I really hate that drunken feeling of being too hot and a little sick. I think it's so unsexy once I get beyond a certain point. I don't really understand how people manage to have drunken shags - tipsy yes, that can definitly help sex but by the time I am actually drunk I just feel hot and uncomfortable. I often feel a little guilty about this as Adam seems quite up for it once we get in whereas I would rather wait for the morning when I am well rested and no longer have a banging headache. Tuesday I was in work at 12pm so decided to leave Adam's at 10.30 so that I would have time for some lunch before the start of my shift. It was fairly steady today in work and lacked the drama and excitement of the weekend, when all hell breaks loose. Joe and I spend much of the day discussing university. Although he has not been (he's now 21 and it looks doubtful that he will ever go), he has several friends who have been through having achieved their degrees. I showed everyone the picture that was taken at the prom. They all said how beautiful my dress and hair looked and how cute Adam and I looked together. It's great at the moment. Everyone is congratulating me on getting into university and having my appearance praised also helps to boast my confident. I must admit that at the moment I am feeling so much better about myself. I think the last year was a bit of a low point. I feel now though that life is picking up: I have a stable love life; feel I am fairly intelligent - at least enough so to get me where I want to go, and this is all that really matters anyway; in terms of my physical appearance a summer spent working out 4/5 times per week has definetly done wonders ( shame it couldn't bring down the blood pressure). After work I went to Studio Strength at the gym. Its a tough work out with weights to music. I absolutely HATE the lunges but I can defiantly feel it working. I doubt it will slim down my legs though. 5 years of swimming, followed by 2years of running and weight training means the muscles in them are really large. Oh well. Tomorrow I shall probably go into Southport to use the gym there and then go swimming.

Sunday 22nd August

Went to work as per usual.  Laura arrived at work 10 minutes late and very very drunk.  Luckily her mother (who also works in the cafe) anticipated this as she had heard her arrive home at 4am in the morning. The only notable customer was a man that smelt really bad. After work I went to the gym.  My workout was fairly unsuccessful.  I managed 10 minutes running on flat (before given up because of a stitch), 15 mins on the cross trainer, 5 on the rower and finally another 10 on the treadmill (on level 2 random).  This is much less than I can usually manage and I put it down to not having been to the gym since the results.  I can't go again now until tuesday when I have a Studio Strength Class so I think when I have a day off on Wednesday I will have to work extremely hard to make up for my inactivity.

After tea Adam came round to my house.  I was feeling really quite sexy and soon pulled him up to my room. Feeling slightly embarrassed by the situation I attempted to take the call, however the signal is so bad in my room that I can't hear a word Helen is saying (crappy Tesco network). Undeterred by this interruption however and we are soon picking up were we left off.  

Monday 22nd
